## Migration: `TimedExecutor` to .NET 8

### Why this breaks

`Thread.Abort()` and `Thread.ResetAbort()` throw `PlatformNotSupportedException` in .NET Core+. `ThreadAbortException` is obsolete. The entire cooperative-cancellation model changed.

### Key pitfalls

| .NET Framework | .NET 8 | Gotcha |
|---|---|---|
| `Thread.Abort()` | `CancellationToken` | Abort was **preemptive**; cancellation is **cooperative** — the work must check the token |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Removed entirely | No equivalent needed |
| `ThreadAbortException` | `OperationCanceledException` | Different exception hierarchy |
| `thread.Join(timeout)` | `Task.WaitAsync(timeout)` | `WaitAsync` doesn't cancel the underlying task — it just stops waiting |
| `default(T)` result captured via closure | `Task<T>` returns directly | Eliminates shared mutable state |

### Migrated code

```csharp
using System;
using System.Threading;
using System.Threading.Tasks;

public class TimedExecutor
{
    /// <summary>
    /// Runs <paramref name="work"/> with a cooperative cancellation timeout.
    /// The delegate MUST observe the CancellationToken for true cancellation.
    /// </summary>
    public async Task<T> ExecuteWithTimeoutAsync<T>(
        Func<CancellationToken, Task<T>> work,
        TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        try
        {
            return await work(cts.Token).WaitAsync(cts.Token);
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }

    // Overload for synchronous work (runs on the thread pool)
    public async Task<T> ExecuteWithTimeoutAsync<T>(
        Func<CancellationToken, T> work,
        TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        return await ExecuteWithTimeoutAsync(
            ct => Task.Run(() => work(ct), ct),
            timeout);
    }
}
```

### Usage comparison

```csharp
// ── Before (.NET Framework) ──
var executor = new TimedExecutor();
var result = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(
    () => SlowDatabaseCall(),
    TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));

// ── After (.NET 8) ──
var executor = new TimedExecutor();

// Async work (preferred)
var result = await executor.ExecuteWithTimeoutAsync(
    async ct => await SlowDatabaseCallAsync(ct),
    TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));

// Sync work (thread-pool fallback)
var result = await executor.ExecuteWithTimeoutAsync(
    ct =>
    {
        ct.ThrowIfCancellationRequested();   // check before expensive work
        return SlowDatabaseCall();
    },
    TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));
```

### Critical caveat

**Cooperative ≠ preemptive.** Unlike `Thread.Abort()`, cancellation only works if the work checks the token. If you're calling code you don't control (e.g., a third-party library with no cancellation support), the task will keep running in the background after the timeout fires. In that case, `WaitAsync` gives you the timeout semantics but does **not** terminate the work — the same fundamental limitation applies to all .NET 8 cancellation.
